# Architecture Guardrails (CephasOps)

When editing or generating code in the backend (Api, Application, Domain, Infrastructure), enforce these rules. They protect against the violations identified in the Level 1–5 engineering maturity audit.

---

## 1. Controllers must not inject DbContext

- **Rule:** No controller in `CephasOps.Api/Controllers` may have `ApplicationDbContext` (or any `DbContext`) as a constructor parameter or private field.
- **Why:** Controllers must use the Application layer for all data access. Direct DbContext bypasses application services and violates Clean Architecture.
- **Do instead:** Inject and use Application services (e.g. `IOrderService`, `IOrderQueryService`, `IStockLedgerService`). If a read or write is needed, add or use an Application service method; do not add DbContext to the controller.

---

## 2. Controllers must call Application services

- **Rule:** Controllers must not perform data access, business logic, or workflow transitions themselves. They must delegate to Application-layer services (interfaces in Application or Domain, implemented in Application or Infrastructure).
- **Why:** Keeps API thin and testable; single place for business rules and transactions.
- **Do instead:** Controller receives request, optionally validates input, calls one or more Application services, maps results to API DTOs, returns HTTP result.

---

## 3. Domain must not reference Infrastructure

- **Rule:** No file in `CephasOps.Domain` may have `using CephasOps.Infrastructure` or reference any type defined in the Infrastructure project.
- **Why:** Domain is the innermost layer; it must not depend on persistence or external concerns.
- **Do instead:** Domain defines interfaces (e.g. `IOrderStore`, `IEventStore`); Infrastructure implements them.

---

## 4. Domain must not reference EF Core

- **Rule:** No file in `CephasOps.Domain` may reference `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` or any EF Core type (DbSet, DbContext, etc.).
- **Why:** Domain must be persistence-ignorant; EF is an Infrastructure concern.
- **Do instead:** Domain uses plain entities and interfaces; EF configurations and DbSets live in Infrastructure.

---

## 5. Services with more than 12 dependencies should be flagged

- **Rule:** When adding or modifying an Application service, if its constructor has more than 12 parameters (dependencies), flag it as a sprawl risk.
- **Why:** OrderService (19 deps) and WorkflowEngineService (11 deps) are already P1 risks; new or growing services should not repeat this.
- **Do instead:** Prefer smaller, focused services; extract a facade or split responsibilities before adding another constructor dependency. Document in an ADR if exceeding 12 is unavoidable.

---

## 6. Services over 1,200 LOC should trigger a warning

- **Rule:** When adding or significantly expanding an Application service file, if the file exceeds 1,200 lines of code, warn that it exceeds the guardrail.
- **Why:** DocumentGenerationService (~1,388 LOC) and others are already oversized; new code should not create new god classes.
- **Do instead:** Split into smaller services or extract cohesive blocks (e.g. template resolution, PDF export) into separate classes.

---

## 7. Avoid circular service dependencies

- **Rule:** Do not introduce a circular dependency where Service A depends on Service B and Service B depends on Service A (directly or via constructor chain). Prefer explicit constructor injection so cycles are visible at compile time; avoid hiding dependencies with `GetRequiredService<T>` in the middle of methods.
- **Why:** SchedulerService ↔ WorkflowEngineService is a known cycle (constructor + runtime resolution); it makes refactoring and testing hard.
- **Do instead:** Break the cycle by introducing an interface or a new component, or by moving the shared behavior to a third service both can depend on.

---

## 8. Background jobs must be idempotent

- **Rule:** All background job executors (IJobExecutor) and legacy job handlers must be designed so that running the same job twice with the same payload produces the same outcome (idempotent). Document the idempotency contract when adding a new job type.
- **Why:** Scheduler overlap or retries can cause the same logical job to run more than once; duplicate side effects (e.g. double notification, double P&L write) must be avoided.
- **Do instead:** Design by payload (e.g. “rebuild P&L for period X” is idempotent); use idempotency keys or “upsert” semantics where applicable. See docs/operations/reliability_audit.md and background_jobs.md.

---

## 9. Workflow transitions must not call controllers

- **Rule:** Workflow transitions must be executed via Application services (e.g. `IWorkflowEngineService`). No code path that performs a workflow transition may call an API controller or HTTP endpoint to achieve the transition.
- **Why:** Transitions are business operations; they belong in the Application layer and must be testable and reusable from jobs, API, and other services.
- **Do instead:** From controllers: call `IWorkflowEngineService.ExecuteTransitionAsync` (or equivalent). From jobs or event handlers: inject and call the same Application service.

---

## 10. Infrastructure code must not appear in Domain

- **Rule:** The Domain project must not contain any Infrastructure-specific code: no EF attributes that are persistence-specific (e.g. avoid if they tie Domain to EF), no connection strings, no file paths to persistence, no references to CephasOps.Infrastructure or Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.
- **Why:** Domain is the core; it must remain portable and free of delivery mechanisms.
- **Do instead:** Keep Domain limited to entities, value objects, domain events, and interfaces for ports (e.g. IEventStore). Implementations live in Application or Infrastructure.

